english:
  title: Record of the Feng Ming Tower
  author: Ha Ryun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Jinju is my native place, and so I know well the beauty of its landscape. Flying Phoenix Mountain spreads its wings and rests to the north, while Gazing Truth Mountain coils like a dragon, embracing the south. Between them flows the great river, while mountains to east and west wind gracefully around, enclosing the land. The Soaring Stone Peak juts forth into the northern stream, and following its natural form, the ancient walls were raised—both formidable and high. Once a tower crowned that peak, and its views were reckoned the finest in the region. Flying Phoenix connects to Long White Mountain and touches the realm of Langfeng; Gazing Truth links to Jiri Mountain, which itself connects to Long White, so all three peaks stand together in majesty. The river waters spring from Jiri, and the streams of countless valleys in its northeast converge into one. With mountains so grand and waters so deep, the vital energy concentrates within, bringing multitudes of people and abundance of goods. Age after age it has produced remarkable talents—and so it has been a great city since ancient times. Is this not fitting?

    Some hundred paces south of the travelers' lodge stands an old three-span structure. Its lower level opens freely for passage, called the Tower Gate, though it had no proper name. Beside it stand dozens of ancient trees, their branches summoning wind and sheltering from sun, while a refreshing breeze rises naturally. Official halls and common dwellings, bamboo groves and flowering trees appear and disappear in succession. Mountain light and water hues, mist and clouds, stars and moon cast their reflection beyond—making this place of excursion truly a paradise at one's very doorstep.

    When Lord Choi, Commissioner of this region and holder of the rank of Upright Counselor, took office, he consulted with the Vice-Administrator Eun to chart a course of good governance. Whatever could be restored from ruin, they pursued. "This province lies at the southern edge," he reflected, "and summer heat is intense. Those who come as envoys or guests should have a cool place to rest. The Stone Peak Tower has long been ruined and lies far from the offices. Why not repair this tower gate? The labor would be slight and the benefit great." He gathered workers, employing the slack season of farming. They straightened what was crooked, replaced what was rotted, added to what was narrow and short, and decorated it with colored plaster. Having completed this, he inscribed it: "Feng Ming Tower"—and asked Chon Je, former magistrate of this province, to commission a record. I accepted.

    Reflecting upon it: the phoenix is an auspicious omen of the sage king. In ancient times when Zhou flourished, the phoenix sang on high hills. Now that an enlightened ruler reigns, walking in benevolence and righteousness, employing the worthy and capable, and holding particularly dear the duty of nurturing the people—Lord Choi, possessed of compassionate and upright character, has assumed the governance of this province to transmit the royal transformation. In naming the tower "Feng Ming," he surely wishes that through virtue both civil and martial, the omen of the singing phoenix might come to our sovereign. One can see how profound is his reverence for the ruler, how deep his devotion.

    I have heard that when Huang Ba served as prefect of Yingchuan in the Han dynasty, a phoenix came to his official residence. His governance became first among all the realm, he was summoned to become prime minister, his accomplishments illuminated his era, and his fame descended to posterity. This is what the people of Jinju hope for Lord Choi—and what he himself must earnestly pursue.

    In my youth, I served my parents in our home at Dang-nam Ward, some two hundred paces from the tower. Upon entering official service, every two or three years I returned home to pay respects. In the spare moments between attending to my parents, I ascended this tower countless times—I could not count them all. Now I am aged, my rank grown high, yet both my parents have passed. The sorrow of the fallen tree and broken wind cuts deeply. I long to resign my post, return to my native place, tend the family graves, and ascend the tower once more with Lord Choi, to admire its renewed form and relive the joys of old wanderings. Yet such things remain beyond my reach.

    I shared lineage with Lord Choi's grandfather, the Lord of Gangneung, in Song-kyong, where I heard the words of our elders and learned that Lord Choi had been schooled in the ways of his household from the beginning. Now hearing that his governance is foremost, I could not refuse this commission, though my words are humble. I offer this record, and with it, my deepest feelings and sorrows.
  footnotes:
    - Flying Phoenix Mountain and Gazing Truth Mountain are real peaks near Jinju that form a natural gate to the city.
    - The phoenix (feng huang) in classical Chinese symbolism represents an auspicious omen accompanying virtuous rulership.
    - Huang Ba was a celebrated Han dynasty administrator whose competent governance was said to have attracted a phoenix—representing heaven's approval of wise rule.
    - The author's melancholy conclusion reflects both his aging exile from home and his deepest longing to return to his birthplace—a common theme in Korean literati of this period.
